Newcastle disease, Mexico
-------------------------
Information received on 12 Feb 2011 from Dr Francisco Velarde Garcia,
Director General de Salud Animal, Servicio Nacional de sanidad,
inocuidad y calidad agroalimentaria (Senasica), Secretaria de
Agricultura, Ganaderia, Desarrollo Rural, Pesca y Alimentacion
(Sagarpa), Mexico DF, Mexico

Summary
Report type Immediate notification
Start date 31 Jan 2011
Date of 1st confirmation of the event 31 Jan 2011
Report date 12 Feb 2011
Date submitted to OIE 12 Feb 2011
Reason for notification Reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence 2003
Manifestation of disease Sub-clinical infection
Causal agent Newcastle disease virus, pathogenic strain
Nature of diagnosis Laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks
Outbreak 1 Nopala de Villagran, Hidalgo, Hidalgo
Date of start of the outbreak 31 Jan 2011
Outbreak status Continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit Farm

Species Birds
Susceptible 500
Cases
Deaths 0
Destroyed 0
Slaughtered 0

Affected Population: Breeding poultry farm; the presence of the
pathogenic strain of the Newcastle disease virus was detected through
routine active surveillance activities implemented nationwide.

Epidemiology - Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection -
Unknown or inconclusive

Epidemiological comments: Identification of the pathogenic strain of
the Newcastle disease virus through active surveillance without
clinical signs of the disease. The disease was present for the last
time in the State of Hidalgo in 2003.

Control measures: Measures applied: Quarantine; Movement control
inside the country; Screening; Zoning; No vaccination; No treatment
of affected animals

Measures to be applied - Stamping out; Disinfection of infected
premises/establishment(s)

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type National Animal Health Diagnostic Services
Center (CENASA) (National laboratory)
Species Birds
Test real-time PCR
Test date 31 Jan 2011
Result Positive

Species Birds
Test virus isolation
Test date 09 Feb 2011
Result Positive

Future Reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Although it has been a long time since Newcastle Disease has been
seen in these states -- since 1982 in Baja California and 2003 in
Hildago -- Mexico has experienced outbreaks in both 2009 and 2010. In
January of 2009, there were 5 outbreaks followed by 15 in February and
18 in March that year. The subsequent 4 months had a total of 16
outbreaks total. In 2010 there were a lower number of outbreaks with 2
in January, 7 in February and 9 in March, with 3 more outbreaks in the
next 2 months.

Certainly with the country's disease history and the fact that both
states had previously been free of disease, it is good that an
aggressive stamping out policy is being put in place. Newcastle
disease can have significant economic effect on commercial poultry
farms and it must be dealt with by strong control and prevention
strategies. Based on the past 2 years, a successful campaign should be
anticipated. The question of the source of new infection remains
unanswered, as is often the case. - Mod.PC]
